# Web3 Doctrine – Why, What, How (plain‑language overview)

## Why Web3 (in simple terms)
- Trust: Partners should be able to click a result and verify "what was run" without asking us. Web3 gives a tamper‑evident receipt for every important action.
- Fair sharing: If our platform helps invent something valuable, the royalty and co‑inventor split should be automatic and transparent.
- c
- Smooth handoffs: Standard "receipts" (attestations) make it easy to replicate results, cite them in dossiers, and license assets.

## Our unique approach (how it works day‑to‑day)
- Every important run (insight, efficacy, benchmark) can mint a short "receipt" on‑chain with a run ID, the profile used (e.g., Baseline/Fusion), and a cryptographic hash of inputs/outputs.
- When our engine contributes to a new design, we can register an IP/royalty agreement (aligned with our co‑inventor doctrine) so value sharing is automated later.
- Cohorts and benchmarks get a public registry entry with their hash and metrics. People can replicate runs and earn bounties for verification.
- Privacy‑first: never put patient data on‑chain. Only short hashes and public metadata; the actual data stays in secure storage.

## Capabilities – what we will ship
1) Provenance Attestations
   - For: `/api/insights/predict_*`, `/api/efficacy/predict`, `/api/datasets/extract_and_benchmark`.
   - Include: `{ run_id, profile, api, inputs_hash, outputs_hash, timestamp }`.
   - Display in FE Provenance bars.

2) IP/royalty contracts (doctrine‑aligned)
   - Co‑inventor shares based on contribution metrics (endpoints used, novelty flags, AI‑authored rationale share).
   - Mirrors platform terms (2–5% royalty, contribution %), links to Dossier and blueprint IDs.

3) Dataset and Benchmark Registry
   - Register dataset manifests (hash‑only) with study/source metadata; publish benchmark metrics (e.g., AUROC/AUPRC) and profile.
   - Support replication bounties; store verifier attestations.

4) Curation and Replication Bounties
   - Literature MoA‑targeted curation bounties; reputation scoring for curators.
   - Benchmark replication bounties to increase trust in metrics.

